500|$|Mounting the {{receiver}} in the Heyford {{was not a}} trivial task; the standard <b>half-wave</b> dipole <b>antenna</b> needed to be about [...] long to detect wavelengths of 6.7m. The solution was eventually found by stringing a cable between the Heyford's fixed landing gear struts. A series of dry cell batteries lining the aircraft floor powered {{the receiver}}, providing high voltage for the CRT through an ignition coil taken from a Ford.|$|R
